afield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Origin: Lacks dated colophon ; calligraphic style, paper, etc. would suggest late 18th or early 19th century.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Former shelfmark: Mich. Isl. Ms. temp. no. 166</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Binding: Pasteboards covered in dark olive-green leather ; Type III binding ; board linings and hinges in yellow-tinted paper ; upper and lower covers carry blind-tooled mandorla, pendants and border in a series of s-shaped stamps flanked by blind rules ; sewn in heavy lime green thread, six stations ; overall in fairly good condition with minor staining, etc.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Support: Wove paper, well-burnished ; written area gold-flecked.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Decoration: Written area gold-flecked and surrounded by frame consisting of narrow bands of red, gold, and blue defined by black fillets ; margin also surrounded by black fillets.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Script: Naskh ; exquisitely executed, large, bold Persianate hand, reminiscent of the style perfected by Aḥmad Nayrīzī (though with the sharp leftward serif on lām appearing only rarely, e.g. p.28) ; partially seriffed with right-sloping head-serif on ṭāʼ and ẓāʼ, free-standing alif sans serif and slightly tapered, two dots occasionally written vertically (one above the other), final yāʼ usually unpointed, sweeping descenders, adhering to baseline apart from occasional superscript of letters, fully vocalized.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Layout: Written in 9 lines per page ; frame-ruled.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Collation: 3 IV(24), III (30) ; quaternions followed by final ternion ; final leaf left blank ; catchwords present ; pagination in pencil, Western numerals, supplied during digitization.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Explicit: "قد تناول الاقرباء اطراف جنازتي وارحم في ذلك البيت المظلم وحشتي وغربتي ووحدتي"</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Incipit: "الهي البستني الخطايا ثوب مذلتي وجللني التباعد منك لباس مسكنتي ..."</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Title supplied by cataloguer.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Ms. codex.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="510" ind1="4" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Kohlberg, E. "Zaynal-ʿĀbidīn (“Ornament of the Worshippers”) ʿAlīb. al-Ḥusayn b. ʿAlī b. Abī d̲j̲ālib." In EI2,</subfield><subfield code="c">Vol. XI, p.481, col. 2</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="520" ind1="8" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Superb specimen of calligraphy employing the munājāt attributed to Zayn al-ʻĀbidīn ʻAlī ibn al-Ḥusayn (d.713?), often included in his collection of prayers al-Ṣaḥīfah al-sajjādīyah.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="541" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="c">Purchase;</subfield><subfield code="a">Purchased in Egypt by Mr. Sulaiman [?] ;</subfield><subfield code="d">Received: 8-21-68 ;</subfield><subfield code="e">(Asadi 690713-156)</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="546" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Arabic.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="561" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">UM library inscription in pencil on p.3 "General Library | 690713-156 | Asadi |8-21-68" ; clean copy.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="650" ind1=" " ind2="0"><subfield code="a">Manuscripts, Arabic</subfield><subfield code="z">Michigan</subfield><subfield code="z">Ann Arbor.</subfield></d